Hi everyone,



We have been exploring evolving, open-ended fitness functions. That means as
new contexts are experienced, the fitness for the superposition of contexts
is explored - obviously changing the experiment classes. Mucks things up a
bit, but helps us simulate the category of &quot;complex adaptive systems&quot;.



The other Ken



From: neat@yahoogroups.com [mailto:neat@yahoogroups.com] On Behalf Of
joel278
Sent: Saturday, April 09, 2011 10:10 AM
To: neat@yahoogroups.com
Subject: [neat] Re: &quot;Survive and Reproduce&quot; as an Objective





Hi Colin,

&gt; The central issue here is how we define fitness. I think the the root
&gt; of your logical error is in considering fitness as a simple metric
&gt; where we can take any two organisms/agents and state that one is
&gt; fitter than the other based on reproductive efficiency and overall
&gt; population size. I believe this view of fitness as a simple linear
&gt; metric is wrong and thus any conclusions we build from this assumption
&gt; are on shaky ground.
&gt; 

Agreeing on an exact definition of biological fitness may be difficult,
especially as there isn&#39;t a complete consensus even among biologists (e.g.
Dawkins lists many different definitions in &quot;Extended Phenotype&quot; ch. 10).
But whether &quot;Survive and Reproduce&quot; is an objective rests not on an exact
definition of biological fitness, but in the disparity between fitness
dynamics in nature and the way that EC traditionally abstracts fitness as an
objective -- which *is* typically a simple metric that compares any two
individuals on a linear scale. 

I completely agree that blindly optimizing this sort of measure is
simplistic and not equivalent with what nature does! However, this is the
traditional approach in EC and is typically what we mean by objectives, not
only in EC but in machine learning as a whole. 

While natural evolution does optimize reproductive efficiency locally within
niches, it does not do so globally. That is, bacteria do not preclude bears.
However, in traditional EC, bacteria would preclude bears, because bacteria
are a simpler, more efficient solution to the problem of
survive-and-reproduce, were survive-and-reproduce the objective. 

So, while we abstract natural evolution as optimizing an objective in EC and
in general look only at the absolute high-fitness individuals, in nature
more inefficient solutions are still interesting. I maintain that solutions
to reproduction such as humans are analogous to incredibly inefficient
pole-balancers that are recognized as interesting in their own right and
still investigated within the search process.

I think if there was an objective in natural evolution, rather than
survive-and-reproduce, it might be &quot;survive-and-reproduce competitively
within your niche or find a new way to live.&quot; But this isn&#39;t an objective in
the traditional sense either, because it is relative not only to the niche
an organism exists within, but also to what niches exist already. In
contrast, typical objectives in EC or machine learning are &quot;find a neural
net that maximizes how far this biped robot walks before it falls&quot; or &quot;find
parameters that minimize the classification error.&quot; These define specific
points in the search space that might count as solutions.

Basically, I believe we are in agreement over most things but perhaps
disagreeing only in definitions? That is, we agree that natural evolution is
more nuanced than the simple treatment of fitness functions in traditional
EC, but may disagree on particular definitions of biological fitness or
objectives.



